subsection.p:
A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers (the plural is matrices). Here is a matrix:

      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4\\
      5 \amp  6 \amp  7 \amp  8\\
      9 \amp  10\amp 11\amp 12
      \end{bmatrix}

      This matrix has 3 rows:





            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4
            \end{bmatrix}
             is row 1,





            \begin{bmatrix}
            5 \amp  6 \amp  7 \amp  8
            \end{bmatrix}
             is row 2 and





         \begin{bmatrix}
         9 \amp  10\amp 11\amp 12
         \end{bmatrix}

         is row 3.

Similarly, the matrix has 4 columns:





         \begin{bmatrix}
         1\\ 5\\ 9 
         \end{bmatrix}

         is  column 1





         \begin{bmatrix}
         2\\ 6\\ 10
         \end{bmatrix}

         is  column 2






         \begin{bmatrix}
         3 \\ 7\\ 11
         \end{bmatrix}

         is  column 3, and





         \begin{bmatrix}
         4\\ 8\\ 12
         \end{bmatrix}

         is  column 4

More generally, a matrix with m rows and n columns is called an m\times n matrix. An m\times n matrix A has the form
A=\begin{bmatrix} a_{1,1} \amp a_{1,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{1,n}\\ a_{2,1} \amp a_{2,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{2,n}\\ \amp \amp \vdots\\ a_{m,1} \amp a_{m,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{m,n} \end{bmatrix}
This notation means that a_{i,j} is the number in both row i and column j. We will call the rows R_1, R_2,\ldots,R_m and the columns C_1, C_2, \ldots,C_n. In other words,
R_i =\begin{bmatrix} a_{i,1} \amp a_{i,2} \amp a_{i,3}, \amp \cdots \amp a_{i,n}\end{bmatrix},
and
C_j=\begin{bmatrix} a_{1,j}\\ a_{2,j}\\ a_{3,j}\\ \vdots\\ a_{m,j} \end{bmatrix}
The notation for this matrix is similar to that used for a system of linear equations, and for good reason. Suppose we have a system of m linear equations in n unknowns:
\begin{array}{lcl} a_{1,1}x_1 + a_{1,2}x_2 +{} \amp \cdots \amp {}+ a_{1,n}x_n = b_1\\ a_{2,1}x_1 + a_{2,2}x_2 +{} \amp \cdots \amp {}+ a_{2,n}x_n = b_2\\ \amp \vdots\\ a_{m,1}x_1 + a_{m,2}x_2 +{} \amp \cdots \amp {}+ a_{m,n}x_n = b_m \end{array}
The coefficient matrix A is then the m\times n matrix
A=\begin{bmatrix} a_{1,1} \amp a_{1,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{1,n}\\ a_{2,1} \amp a_{2,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{2,n}\\ \amp \amp \vdots\\ a_{m,1} \amp a_{m,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{m,n} \end{bmatrix}
and the augmented matrix of the system is the m\times( n+1) matrix
A=\begin{bmatrix} a_{1,1} \amp a_{1,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{1,n}\amp b_1\\ a_{2,1} \amp a_{2,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{2,n}\amp b_2\\ \amp \amp \vdots\amp \amp \\ a_{m,1} \amp a_{m,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{m,n}\amp b_m \end{bmatrix}
Hence the augmented is the coefficient matrix with one column (the constants on the right side of the equations) added. To emphasize the extra column, the augmented matrix is sometimes written as
A=\left[\begin{array}{llcl|l} a_{1,1} \amp a_{1,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{1,n}\amp b_1\\ a_{2,1} \amp a_{2,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{2,n}\amp b_2\\ \amp \amp \vdots\amp \amp \\ a_{m,1} \amp a_{m,2} \amp \cdots \amp a_{m,n}\amp b_m \end{array}\right]

