subsection.p:
The matrix is in row echelon form. Now we can determine all of the solutions to the original system of linear equations. The first nonzero entry in the first row is in the first column, the column associated with x_1. The first nonzero entry in the second row, similarly, is associated with x_2. We assign parameters to the other variables: x_3=s and x_4=t. The second row then tells us that x_2-\frac34s =-\frac12 , or x_2=\frac34s-\frac12. Now that we know x_2, we can use the first row to find x_1: we get x_1-\frac23x_2-\frac13s+\frac13t=\frac13. We substitute in our known value for x_2 into this equation, and after some simplification, we get x_1=\tfrac56s-\tfrac13t. In summary, we have: All solutions to
\begin{array}{r} 3x_1-2x_2-x_3+x_4=1\\ 6x_1-8x_2+x_3+2x_4=4 \end{array}
are of the form
\begin{array}{rcl} x_1\amp =\amp \tfrac56s-\tfrac13t\\ x_2\amp =\amp -\tfrac12 +\tfrac34 s\\ x_3\amp =\amp s\\ x_4\amp =\amp t \end{array}
where s and t are any real numbers. More compactly, we write this as (x_1,x_2,x_3,x_4)= \tfrac56s-\tfrac13t,-\tfrac12 +\tfrac34 s,s,t). In other words, for any assignment of real numbers to s and t, we get a solution to the system of linear equations.

Now consider another example with the equations

          \begin{array}{lrcc}
          x_1  + 2x_2 \amp -2x_3  \amp =\amp  -1\\
          3x_1 -2x_2  \amp -4x_3 \amp =\amp  3\\
          4x_1        \amp -2x_3 \amp =\amp  -2\\
          -x_1 -x_2   \amp +2x_3 \amp =\amp 0
          \end{array}

          and its corresponding augmented matrix as it is changed by Gaussian elimination:

          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp -2\amp -1 \\
          3\amp -2\amp -4\amp 3\\
          4\amp 0\amp -2\amp -2\\
          -1\amp -1\amp 2\amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{array}{c}
          \\R_2 \leftarrow R_2-3R_1\\ R_3\gets R_3-4R_1\\ R_4\gets R_4+R_1
          \end{array}

          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp -2\amp -1 \\
          0\amp -8\amp 2\amp 6\\
          0\amp -8\amp 6\amp 2\\
          0\amp 1\amp 0\amp -1
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{array}{c}
          R_2\gets-\frac18 R_2\\ R_3\gets R_3+8R_2\\R_4\gets R_4-R_2
          \end{array}


          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp -2\amp -1 \\
          0\amp 1\amp -\frac14\amp -\frac34\\
          0\amp 0\amp 4\amp -4\\
          0\amp 0\amp \tfrac14 \amp -\tfrac14
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{array}{c}
           R_3 \gets \frac14 R_3\\R_4\gets R_4-\frac14 R_3
          \end{array}


          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp -2\amp -1 \\
          0\amp 1\amp -\frac14\amp -\frac34\\
          0\amp 0\amp 1\amp -1\\
          0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}

          The last row, for any choice of x_1, x_2, x_3, reduces to
          0=0, so any solution of the associated first three equations will also be
          a solution to the last one. In other words, the last row of the matrix has no effect
          on the solution set and may be dropped from the matrix. The third row gives
          x_3=-1. The second row gives x_2=-1 and the first row gives x_1=-1.
          Hence there is one solution: (x_1,x_2,x_3)=(-1,-1,-1).

Now change the equations from the last example very slightly (the right-hand side of the last equation is changed from 0 to 1):
\begin{array}{rcc} x_1 + 2x_2 -2x_3 \amp =\amp -1\\ 3x_1-2x_2-4x_3 \amp =\amp 3\\ 4x_1 -2x_3 \amp =\amp -2\\ -x_1-x_2+2x_3 \amp =\amp 1 \end{array}
The Gaussian elimination is almost identical as
\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 2\amp -2\amp -1 \\ 3\amp -2\amp -4\amp 3\\ 4\amp 0\amp -2\amp -2\\ -1\amp -1\amp 2\amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
is reduced to
\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 2\amp -2\amp -1 \\ 0\amp 1\amp -\frac14\amp -\frac34\\ 0\amp 0\amp 1\amp -1\\ 0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 1
\end{bmatrix}

example.p:
Consider the system of linear equations:

          \begin{array}{rcl}
          x+y+z\amp =\amp  1\\
          2x+y+z \amp =\amp  2\\
          3x+ay+bz\amp =\amp c
          \end{array}

          We wish to know the values of a, b and c for which there 
          are there no solutions, one solution or more than one solution.
          To solve this problem, we apply Gaussian elimination to the augmented matrix: 


          \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 1\amp 1\amp 1\\2\amp 1\amp 1\amp 2\\3\amp a\amp b\amp c \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{matrix}R_2\gets R_2-2R_1\\ R_3\gets R_3-3 R_1\end{matrix}


          \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 1\amp 1\amp 1\\0\amp -1\amp -1\amp 0\\0\amp a-3\amp b-3\amp c-3 \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{matrix}R_2\gets -R_2\\R_3\gets R_3-(a-3)R_2\end{matrix}


          \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 1\amp 1\amp 1\\0\amp 1\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp b-a\amp c-3 \end{bmatrix}


          An analysis of the last row tells us everything: If b-a\not=0,
          then there is exactly one solution. If b-a=0, and c-3\not=0, 
          then there are no solutions. Otherwise (when
          b=a and c=3) there are an infinite number of solutions.

solution.p:
We put the augemented matrix into row echelon form:

            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0\\
            2 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 3\\
            \end{bmatrix}
            \\
            \begin{array}{l}
            R_2\gets R_2 - R_1\\
            R_3\gets R_3-2R_1
            \end{array}
            \\
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp -2\\
            0 \amp -5 \amp 3 \amp -1\\
            \end{bmatrix}
            \\
            \begin{array}{l}
            R_2\gets -R_2\\
            \end{array}
            \\
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp -5 \amp 3 \amp -1\\
            \end{bmatrix}
            \\
            R_3\gets R_3+5R_2
            \\
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 9\\
            \end{bmatrix}
            \\
            R_3\gets \frac13 R_3
            \\
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3\\
            \end{bmatrix}

            The last row gives z=3. The second row gives y=2. The first row gives
            x=2-2y+z=2-4+3=1, and so there is a unique solution (x,y,z)=(1,2,3).

introduction.p:
In summary, we can say the following:
If the reduced row echelon form has a row of the form [0,0,\dots,0,1], then the system of linear equations has no solution.
If the reduced row echelon form has no free variables, then it looks like:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp c_1\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp c_2\\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp c_3\\ \amp \amp \amp \vdots \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp c_{n-1}\\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp c_n \end{bmatrix}
and there is a unique solution, namely, x_1=c_1, x_2=c_2,\dots x_n=c_n.
If the reduced row echelon form has free variables, then there are an infinite number of solutions. Indeed, the parameter assigned to any one free variable can take on an infinite number of values.
Consider the following system of linear equations:
\begin{array}{rl} x_1-x_2+2x_3-x_4 \amp = -1 \\ 2x_1+x_2-2x_3-2x_4 \amp = -2 \\ -x_1+2x_2-4x_3+x_4 \amp = 1 \\ 3x_1-3x_4 \amp = -3 \end{array}
The augmented matrix is then put into reduced row echelon form:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp -1\\ 2 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp -2 \amp -2\\ -1 \amp 2 \amp -4 \amp 1 \amp 1\\ 3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}
\begin{array}{rl} R_2 \amp \gets R_2-2R_1\\ R_3 \amp \gets R_3+R_1\\ R_4 \amp \gets R_4-3R_1 \end{array}

p.me:
\begin{array}{rl}
      R_1 \amp \gets R_1 + R_2\\
      R_3 \amp \gets R_3- R_2\\
      R_4 \amp \gets R_4- 3R_2
      \end{array}

subsection.p:
Since the matrix A= \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 2\amp 3\amp 4\amp 5 \\ 6\amp 7\amp 8\amp 9\amp 10 \\ 11\amp 12\amp 13\amp 14\amp 15 \\ \end{bmatrix}
has a reduced row echelon form of
\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0\amp -1\amp -2\amp -3 \\ 0\amp 1\amp 2\amp 3\amp 4 \\ 0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0 \\ \end{bmatrix}
the rank of A is 2.

solution.p:
We put the augmented matrix in reduced row echelon form:
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ \end{bmatrix}\\ \rowsub3{}1\\ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1\amp -1 \amp 0\\ \end{bmatrix}\\ \rowadd1{}2\\ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0\amp -1 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1\amp -1 \amp 0\\ \end{bmatrix}\\ \rowsub3{}2\\ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 0\amp 0 \amp 0\\ \end{bmatrix}
We then have that z is a free variable that may be set to t. All solutions are then of the form (x,y,z)=(t,t,t), which implies that x=y and y=z.

