example.p:
Consider the system of linear equations

\begin{array}{rl}
x+y+z \amp= 2\\
x+2y+z\amp=3\\
x+2y-3z \amp=2
\end{array}

The augmented matrix is


\begin{bmatrix}
1\amp1\amp1\amp2\\
1\amp2\amp1\amp3\\
1\amp2\amp-3\amp2
\end{bmatrix}

whose reduced row echelon form is 

\begin{bmatrix}
1\amp0\amp0\amp\frac34\\
0\amp1\amp0\amp1\\
0\amp0\amp1\amp\frac14
\end{bmatrix}


This means that there is a single solution: (x,y,z)=(\frac34,1,\frac14).
Here are the three planes corresponding to the three equations:

Consider the system of linear equations
\begin{array}{rl} x+y-z \amp= 3\\ x+y+z\amp=1\\ 2x+2y \amp=4 \end{array}
The augmented matrix is
\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp1\amp-1\amp3\\ 1\amp1\amp1\amp1\\ 2\amp2\amp0\amp4 \end{bmatrix}
whose reduced row echelon form is
\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp1\amp0\amp2\\ 0\amp0\amp1\amp-1\\ 0\amp0\amp0\amp0 \end{bmatrix}
This means y=t, x=2-t and z=-1 so that (x,y,z)=(2-t,t,-1) is a solution for any real number t.

Consider the system of linear equations

\begin{array}{rl}
2x-y+z \amp= 1\\
x+y+z\amp=2\\
4x+y+3z \amp=3
\end{array}

The augmented matrix is

\begin{bmatrix}
2\amp-1\amp1\amp1\\
1\amp1\amp1\amp2\\
4\amp1\amp3\amp3
\end{bmatrix}

whose reduced row echelon form is

\begin{bmatrix}
1\amp0\amp\frac23\amp0\\
0\amp1\amp\frac13\amp0\\
0\amp0\amp0\amp1
\end{bmatrix}

The last row indicates that there is no solution.

Consider the system of linear equations

\begin{array}{rl}
2x-y+z \amp= 1\\
2x-y+z \amp= 3\\
2x-y+z \amp=5
\end{array}

The augmented matrix is


\begin{bmatrix}
2\amp-1\amp1\amp1\\
2\amp-1\amp1\amp3\\
2\amp-1\amp1\amp5
\end{bmatrix}

whose reduced row echelon form is

\begin{bmatrix}
1\amp -\frac12\amp\frac12\amp0\\
0\amp0\amp0\amp1\\
0\amp0\amp0\amp0\\
\end{bmatrix}

The middle row indicates that there is no solution.
